Introduction ¶

Phase 1 summary¶

In phase 1 report, the overall customer satisfactory level of an airline passenger was analysed based on various explanatory/descriptive variables i.e. passenger satisfaction levels for various services offered by the USA airline. The report was focused on exploring the relationships between different types of customers and their response to certain aspects of their flight experience, and how these experiences affected their overall flying experience.

After thoroughly studying the dataset, we started by performing data cleaning procedures to the the Airline passenger satisfaction dataset. We dropped any redundant columns and renamed most of the column names for better readability. The next step was to check for any missing values and outliers in the dataset to make sure that extreme values do not contaminate the overall dataset. Finally, the data type of each features were also took into consideration and changed some of it (like changing float to int which was caused by null responses in some of the columns) for better consistency and usability of dataset. After applying all the required data cleaning and pre-processing techniques to make sure that the data is appropriate to be used in phase 2, we randomly sampled 5000 rows (since there were 119204 rows in total) and generated various visualisations from them.

A range of data visualisations techniques were utilised to get a better insight into the relationships within the dataset, from univariate plots representing the overall satisfaction ratings (target feature) to multi-variate plots displaying various factors influencing the customer feedback.

It was concluded that the overall satisfaction feedback for the airline services was mostly neutral or negative. Moreover, the flying class had a significant impact on the satisfaction levels, customers opted to fly lower class returned an overall negative response compared to upper business class. All of this was supported using a range of data visualisations techniques to further visualise any correlations.

Report Overview¶

In this second phase of the project, we aim to apply statistical modeling techniques to the pre- processed Airline satisfaction dataset obtained from phase 1 report. This will help us approach data analysis in a strategic way and make better real world predictions. In order to make the problem a regression one, a continuous numerical feature, arrival delay in minutes will be selected instead of binary categorical variable. This is to also ensure that the features used is statistically powerful, has simpler interpretation and is suitable for modeling.

The aim of this project is to put into application predictive modeling techniques to explore the relationship between explanatory variables and response variable. A statistical model will be produced after applying various modeling techniques like backward feature selection for making any patterns present observable. As with many aspects of data modeling, there will be some limitations on its usability which will be discussed later in the report.

Overview of methodology¶

We first gather the cleaned data from the phase 1 report. After this, one- hot encoding will be implemented depending upon the type of variables. We begin by selecting most appropriate predictor and a response variables. With the help of a regression formula, all the independent variables are transformed to a string which will later help us in ordinary least square method. The multiple linear regression to be modeled attempts to demonstrate the relation amongst dependent and independent variables using statistical techniques. We begin by selecting most appropriate predictor and a response variables. Model fitting will be utilised to predicts the arrival delay of airlines in minutes. In order to convert categorical features to multiple binary features, one - hot encoding will be implemented.To get a better view of the fitted values, a new data frame is created containing the arrival delay column from the original data frame, regression residuals and the fitted values (predicted values) obtained from OLS. To further visualise the 3 column data frame, graphs are plotted comparing each variable which will help perform diagnostic checks on the model.

After this, a fitting model method - backward feature selection is implemented to make sure that the least statistically significant variables are eliminated i.e. variables with high p-values. Elimination of these insignificant variables reduces the risks of unnecessary complications to the model. Further diagnostic checks are conducted on this reduced model obtained from backward feature selection which will contribute to improving the efficiency of the a model.

Statistical Modeling ¶

Model Overview¶

We are using linear multiple linear regression as our principle statistical technique. The multiple linear regression model attempts to demonstrate the relation amongst dependent and independent variables using statistical techniques. Model fitting technique will be utilised to predicts the arrival delay of airlines in minutes. With the help of a regression formula, all the independent variables are transformed to a string which will later help us in ordinary least square (OLS) modeling. one - hot encoding will be implemented which will make the variables more expressive and to ensure that the machine learning algorithm works efficiently. This is then used to get to modeling of one- hot encoded data usinf OLS. Although doing this provides us with a extensive details and figures, p-values and R-squared values will be helpful the most. Then, backward feature selection is helpful to make sure that the least statistically significant variables are eliminated i.e. variables with high p-values. Elimination of these insignificant variables reduces the risks of unnecessary complications to the model

With the help of pandas, get_dummies() function can be used to easily to transform categorical features to one-hot-encoding.

Ordinary least squares¶

Ordinary least squares regression creates a model by estimating unknown parameters which will reduce the total squared errors between the predictor variable and the response variable. We can now proceed to modeling the prepared data with OLS regression.

This is done using statsmodels module to implement OLS method of regression which takes in 'regression_formula' as the formula parameter and 'encoded_df' as the dataframe, both constructed in previous steps.

Obtaining the required measure of model performance

Out of all the extensive figures presented, the main focus is on p- values and the R squared values. The R- squared value of 0.929 conveys the proportion of the variance for a dependent variable that is attributed to the independent variable, in this case its 92%. This indicates that its a good fit as the model explains a high 92% of the variability of the response data around its mean.

Another significant figure to consider is the p-value, probability that the test results are at least as extreme as the observed results (assuming null hypothesis is correct). There seems to be several variables with p-value greater than the 0.05, indicating weaker evidence against the null hypothesis. Therefore, we accept the null hypothesis, and reject the alternative hypothesis.

Full Model Diagnostic Checks¶

Now that the regression model is fitted, it is important to inspect the model's regression assumptions. Not inspecting this will likely result in biased and inaccurate Ordinary Least Squares estimations. This may make our conclusions made on the based on OLS model less reliable.

There are some assumptions made with linear regression. Before drawing any inferences, these assumptions must be met. The regression model's key assumptions are:

  • The variance of the errors is constant
  • The residuals are statistically independent
  • The residual distribution of the model is normal
  • The relationship between the independent and the target variable is linear

The first diagnostic check is to analyse the leftovers i.e. the residuals which will reveal any patterns that are inexplicable. For analyzing the residuals, we can use a residuals by predicted delay plot. Doing this will. help us work out if fixing the errors in the data set will result improved estimates produced by the model.

Backward feature selection¶

Now that the diagnostic checks have been completed, we can start the variable elimination process with backward feature selection. This is necessary as the assumptions validated above do not guarantee a valid regression model, for this reason we can obtain a reduced model by eliminating insignificant features. Doing this reduces chances of performance issue like slow processing of data. This will also assist the machine learning model in forming finer predictions. The following code will help in backward feature selection Credit

In [162]:
# create the patsy model description from formula
patsy_description = patsy.ModelDesc.from_formula(regression_formula)

# initialize feature-selected fit to full model
linreg_fit = model_full_fitted

# do backwards elimination using p-values
p_val_cutoff = 0.05

## WARNING 1: The code below assumes that the Intercept term is present in the model.
## WARNING 2: It will work only with main effects and two-way interactions, if any.

print('\nPerforming backwards feature selection using p-values:')



while True:

    # uncomment the line below if you would like to see the regression summary
    # in each step:
    ### print(linreg_fit.summary())

    pval_series = linreg_fit.pvalues.drop(labels='Intercept')
    pval_series = pval_series.sort_values(ascending=False)
    term = pval_series.index[0]
    pval = pval_series[0]
    if (pval < p_val_cutoff):
        break
    term_components = term.split(':')
    print(f'\nRemoving term "{term}" with p-value {pval:.4}')
    if (len(term_components) == 1): ## this is a main effect term
        patsy_description.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[0])]))    
    else: ## this is an interaction term
        patsy_description.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[0]), 
                                                        patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[1])]))    
        
    linreg_fit = smf.ols(formula=patsy_description, data=encoded_df).fit()
    
###
## this is the clean fit after backwards elimination
model_reduced_fitted = smf.ols(formula = patsy_description, data = encoded_df).fit()
###
    
#########
print("\n***")
print(model_reduced_fitted.summary())
print("***")
print(f"Regression number of terms: {len(model_reduced_fitted.model.exog_names)}")
print(f"Regression F-distribution p-value: {model_reduced_fitted.f_pvalue:.4f}")
print(f"Regression R-squared: {model_reduced_fitted.rsquared:.4f}")
print(f"Regression Adjusted R-squared: {model_reduced_fitted.rsquared_adj:.4f}")

Backward feature selection is performed using p- values of each variable. The standard p- value threshold is 0.05 or 5%, however this value is not appropriate in every condition. With the p-value of 0.05, there are a total of 20 columns eliminated leaving only 3 regression terms. Logically, the only term that makes sense to feed to the model is departure_delay, as this will greatly affect the arrival time of the airline (If the airline departs late, it is highly likely to arrive late at its destination).

A new data frame residual_reduced is created similar to the data frame created for the full model. This will help us explore the reduced model further.

Since there are a large number of columns eliminated due to a low cut off p- value, a trial can be conducted using a new p- value threshold and backward selection can be re- performed with this adjusted p -value. The new p- values will simply be adjusted based on variables that have a significant effect on the target feature, instead of making use of Holm correction or Hochberg correction method.

Features such as depart_arrive_time has an impact on the arrival delay time. Moreover its p- value is just above the 0.05 threshold. flight_distance can also influence arrival delay of the airline, however, due to its p- value being significantly higher than the threshold p -value . Therefore, depart_arrive_time will be accommodated in the model instead of fully eliminating it. We perform backward feature selection again with a new modified p -value of 0.079.

In [164]:
# create the patsy model description from formula
patsy_description = patsy.ModelDesc.from_formula(regression_formula)

# initialize feature-selected fit to full model
linreg_fit = model_full_fitted

# do backwards elimination using p-values
p_val_cutoff = 0.079

## WARNING 1: The code below assumes that the Intercept term is present in the model.
## WARNING 2: It will work only with main effects and two-way interactions, if any.

print('\nPerforming backwards feature selection using p-values:')



while True:

    # uncomment the line below if you would like to see the regression summary
    # in each step:
    ### print(linreg_fit.summary())

    pval_series = linreg_fit.pvalues.drop(labels='Intercept')
    pval_series = pval_series.sort_values(ascending=False)
    term = pval_series.index[0]
    pval = pval_series[0]
    if (pval < p_val_cutoff):
        break
    term_components = term.split(':')
    print(f'\nRemoving term "{term}" with p-value {pval:.4}')
    if (len(term_components) == 1): ## this is a main effect term
        patsy_description.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[0])]))    
    else: ## this is an interaction term
        patsy_description.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[0]), 
                                                        patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[1])]))    
        
    linreg_fit = smf.ols(formula=patsy_description, data=encoded_df).fit()
    
###
## this is the clean fit after backwards elimination
model_reduced_fitted = smf.ols(formula = patsy_description, data = encoded_df).fit()
###
    
#########
print("\n***")
print(model_reduced_fitted.summary())

Critique and Limitations ¶

The modeling methods were implemented mostly correctly, aiming at the accuracy of the results. However, like all other data models, there were a set of limitations to it. In pahse 1, the target feature selected was unsuitable as it was a categorical feature instead of a continuos numerical one. For this reason, a new target feature, arrival delay had to be selected. Overfitting is one of the other limitations. Overfitting the model is simple, and it can progress to the point where it begins to model the data's random errors rather than the relationship between the variables. As the Airline dataset contained large amount of rows, it occurs most common when there are too many parameters in relation to the number of samples. Another limitation is that it makes the assumption that there is no (or little) multicollinearity between the variables (i.e., the variables are unrelated to one another)1 – which might make the model exceedingly unstable. This is a diffucult to test and delete, despite how straightforward it is. It is sensitive to outliers and poor-quality data. In the actual world, data is frequently tainted for outliers and poor data quality. The linear regression model will be distorted away from the genuine underlying relationship if the number of outliers compared to non-outlier data points is greater than a few.

Moreover, since there was one hot encoding implemented, it makes it more difficult for the model to link relationships amongst variables reducing the performance.In addition, adjusting p value resulted in selection of additional columns that were not intended in making of the trial dataframe with adjusted p value.

Summary and Conclusion ¶

Project Summary¶

The overall customer satisfaction level of an airline passenger was analysed in phase 1 report based on various explanatory/descriptive variables, namely, passenger satisfaction levels for various services offered by the USA airline. The overall satisfaction feedback for airline services was mostly neutral or negative, according to the findings. To further visualise any correlations, all of this was supported by a variety of data visualisation techniques. However, selecting numerical variable over categorical variable would have enhanced the analysis.

In phase 2, multiple linear regression technique was used to predict arrival delay in minutes of US airline which was influenced by various independent variables. After gathering the data from phase 1 report, one-hot coding was performed. After finding the outliers and multi-collinear, the columns that un-aid in prediction process were removed. One - hot encoding made the variables more expressive and ensured that the machine learning algorithm worked efficiently with categorical data. P-values and R-squared values were most helpful even though it provided us with extensive details and figures. Subsequently, two new data frame was created containing the arrival delay column from the original data frame, regression residuals and the fitted values (predicted values) obtained from OLS (For both Full model and reduced model). Backward feature helped to ensure that the least statistically significant variables were eliminated. Further diagnostic checks were conducted on this reduced model obtained from backward feature selection. Graphs were plotted comparing each variable which helped perform further diagnostic checks on the reduced model to endure increased accuracy of predictions from the model.

Summary Findings¶

The model had a R squared value of 92 percent and a model p-value ranging from 0 to 0.9 after feature selection we were left with 3 variables with p-values of 0. The graphs plotted for actual vs predicted supported the assumption of lniearity between those 2 variables. The residuals that were plotted were slightly overestimated for the shorter arrival delay predictions and slightly under-estimated when predicting longer arrival delays of the Airline. A log transformation for predicted delay vaules was applied to the strongly skewed plot to obtain a more meaningful and readable data.

After performing various diagnostic checks, the reduced model showed very similar trends to the full model.With such a high R squared value of 0.092, we can demonstrate that the model is accurate and can correctly estimate delay times, with the exception of a few outliers.

Conclusion¶

In simple terms, statistical modeling is a simplified, mathematically-formalized way to approximate reality (i.e. what generates your data) and optionally to make predictions from this approximation. The results of the statistical modelling show that the factors utilised are reliable and good indicators for predicting airline delay durations for the United StatesAirlines with some minor limitations. We saw a good link between several independent variables and the arrival delay, which provided us a fair indication of what to expect from statistical modelling. The statistical modelling results following phase 2 backed up our idea even more. Managing timings of flights can be a challenging task for airlinr companies with alot of factoes affecting this. These reports would help the U.S airline company to prioritise and manage time delays for their flights.
